Part 1: Independent measures

Rewind

Hypothesis testing:

  • relied on the z-score
    • key here: the standard error \(SE\)
    • problem: we need \(\sigma\) for the \(SE\) but usually dont know \(\sigma\)
  • new kid on the block: t-statistic
    • trick here: we use the estimated standard error \(s_{M}\)
    • t-distribution
    • one-sample t-test

One-sample t-test

Is the worry score (\(M=6.55\), \(SD=1.76\)) significantly larger than the neutral mid-point?

Steps:

  1. we want to calculate: \(t=\frac{M-\mu}{s_{M}}\)
  2. we need: the estimated standard error \(s_{M} = \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} = \sqrt{\frac{s^2}{n}}\)
  3. we need: the sample variance \(s^2 = \frac{SS}{n-1}=\frac{SS}{df}\)
  4. we need: the degrees of freedom \(df =n-1\)

Worry example

We know \(n=2500\), \(s=SD=1.76\), \(M=6.55\) and \(\mu=5\):

\(s_{M} = \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} = \frac{1.76}{\sqrt{2500}} =\frac{1.76}{50.00}= 0.04\)

\(t=\frac{6.55-5.00}{0.04} = 38.75\)

Reported as: \(t(2499) = 38.75\)

The critical region for \(\alpha =.01\) and \(df > 120 \rightarrow 2.326\).

We conclude that the worry score is significantly larger than 5.

Independent samples designs

But this was all just on one sample (here: a sample of UK adults)

  • but in many cases, we need to compare two samples (esp.in experimental research)
  • idea: two groups of participants that are independent (hence: called a between-subjects design)

Scenario

Statistics exam grade and espresso intake

  • Group 1: No espresso
  • Group 2: 3 espressos before the exam
  • random assignment to conditions
  • each group had \(n=50\)

RQ: does espresso intake result in a better exam grade?

Our data

Group 1: No espresso

\(M_1 = 6.95\) and \(SD_1=0.87\)

Group 2: 3 espressos before the exam

\(M_2 = 7.19\) and \(SD_2=1.72\)

What now?

  • the one-sample t-test idea doesnt work
  • we now need a way to compare two group means

How do we accommodate that in our t-formula \(t=\frac{M-\mu}{s_{M}}\)?

What about the hypotheses? And the standard error?

Part 2: The t-statistic for independent measures

Hypotheses

The one-sample case: deviation from reference value (e.g.5)

\(H_0: \mu=5\)

(directional) \(H_1: \mu>5\)

(non-directional) \(H_1: \mu \neq 5\)

Hypotheses

The two independent samples case:

Remember: we are talking about two means now

\(H_0: \mu_1 - \mu_2 = 0\) (there is no difference between the population means)

\(H_1: \mu_1 - \mu_2 \neq 0\) (there is a difference between the population means)

This is the same as \(H_1: \mu_1 \neq \mu_2\)

Hypotheses

Same idea again:

We can have one-tailed or two-tailed alternative hypotheses:

(non-directional) \(H_1: \mu_1 - \mu_2 \neq 0\) (the means differ)

(directional) \(H_1: \mu_1 > \mu_2\) (the mean of group 1 is larger the mean of group 2)

(directional) \(H_1: \mu_1 < \mu_2\) (the mean of group 2 is larger the mean of group 1)

The t-statistic

Same approach: if for the one-sample test \(t=\frac{M-\mu}{s_{M}}\)

then for the two independent samples test:

\(t=\frac{(M_1-M_2)-(\mu_1 - \mu_2)}{estimated\ SE}\)

For a null-hypothesis test, we know that:

\(H_0: \mu_1 - \mu_2 = 0\), \(t=\frac{(M_1-M_2)}{estimated\ SE}\)

But what about the standard error?

The standard error

The one-sample case: \(s_{M} = \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}\)

= the amount of variability in the sample

In the two independent samples case, we have 2 samples:

So: \(SE_{independent} = error\ of\ both\ sources\)

SE for the difference

We know how to obtain \(s_{M_1}\) and \(s_{M_2}\):

\(s_{M_1} = \sqrt{\frac{s^2_1}{n_1}}\)

Lets do this for our scenario.

Espresso example

Group 1: No espresso > \(M_1 = 6.95\) and \(SD_1=0.87\)

Group 2: 3 espressos > \(M_2 = 7.19\) and \(SD_2=1.72\)

The combination of the two is:

\(s_{M_1 - M_2} = \sqrt{{\frac{s^2_1}{n_1}+\frac{s^2_2}{n_2}}}\)

General formula

\(s_{M_1 - M_2} = \sqrt{{\frac{s^2_1}{n_1}+\frac{s^2_2}{n_2}}}\)

But this assumes that the sample sizes are equal (\(n_1 = n_2\)).

If, say \(n_1 = 1000\) and \(n_2=50\), we know that \(n_1\) results in a better approximation of the population. So \(n_1\) should be weighted more than \(n_2\).

For this, we need the pooled variance!

Pooled variance

Conceptually: takes into account the sample size (i.e.the amount of information) that we have for each sample.

Statistically: we do this via the degrees of freedom \(df\)

Sample variance

For a single sample: \(s^2 = \frac{SS}{df}\)

Suppose: \(SS = 37.09\) and \(n=50\), then

\(s^2 = \frac{37.09}{50-1} = 0.76\)

The pooled variance, simply combines these for two samples

Pooled variance

\(s_{p}^2 = \frac{SS_1+SS_2}{df_1 + df_2}\)

Our example:

Group 1: \(SS_1 = 37.09\) and \(df=50-1=49\)

Group 2: \(SS_2 = 144.96\) and \(df=50-1=49\)

So: \(s_{p}^2=\frac{SS_1+SS_2}{df_1 + df_2}=\frac{37.09+144.96}{49+49} = 1.86\)

Pooling

Compare \(s_{p}^2=\frac{SS_1+SS_2}{df_1 + df_2}=\frac{37.09+144.96}{49+49} = 1.86\)

to:

  • \(s_{1}^2 = \frac{SS_1}{df_1} = \frac{37.09}{49} = 0.76\)
  • \(s_{2}^2 = \frac{SS_2}{df_2} = \frac{144.96}{49} = 2.96\)

For \(n_1=n_2\), the pooled variance is the mean of the two sample variances!

But this is not true for unequal sample sizes

Pooling for different n

Suppose: \(SS_1 = 37.09\) with \(n_1=50\) // \(SS_2 = 144.09\) with \(n_1=100\)

\(s_{p}^2=\frac{SS_1+SS_2}{df_1 + df_2}=\frac{37.09+144.96}{49+99} = 1.23\)

This is no longer the mean of the two:

  • \(s_{1}^2 = \frac{SS_1}{df_1} = \frac{37.09}{49} = 0.76\)
  • \(s_{2}^2 = \frac{SS_2}{df_2} = \frac{144.96}{99} = 1.46\)
  • the (unweighted) mean would be: 1.11

In doubt: pooling

\(s_{p}^2=\frac{SS_1+SS_2}{df_1 + df_2}\)

Can also be written as:

\(s_{p}^2=\frac{df_1*s_{1}^2+df_2*s_{2}^2}{df_1 + df_2}\)

Now we use all that pooling for the standard error.

Remember: we need the SE

\(t=\frac{(M_1-M_2)}{estimated\ SE}\)

\(S_{M_1 - M_2} = \sqrt{{\frac{s^2_p}{n_1}+\frac{s^2_p}{n_2}}}\)

For our case:

Pooled variance: \(s_{p}^2=\frac{SS_1+SS_2}{df_1 + df_2}=\frac{37.09+144.96}{49+49} = 1.86\)

Could also have been calculated based on the \(SDs\) given:

\(s_{p}^2=\frac{df_1*s_{1}^2+df_2*s_{2}^2}{df_1 + df_2}=\frac{df_1*0.87^2+df_2*1.72^2}{df_1 + df_2}=\frac{49*0.87^2+49*1.72^2}{49+49} = 1.86\)

So our \(S_{M_1 - M_2}\) becomes

\(S_{M_1 - M_2}\)

\(S_{M_1 - M_2} = \sqrt{{\frac{s^2_p}{n_1}+\frac{s^2_p}{n_2}}}=\sqrt{{\frac{1.86}{50}+\frac{1.86}{50}}} = 0.27\)

Note: for our equal \(n\) example, we would have gotten this without pooling:

\(s_{M_1 - M_2} = \sqrt{{\frac{s^2_1}{n_1}+\frac{s^2_2}{n_2}}}=\sqrt{{\frac{0.76}{50}+\frac{2.96}{50}}} = 0.27\)

Back to t

\(t=\frac{(M_1-M_2)-(\mu_1 - \mu_2)}{s_{(M_1-M_2)}}\)

For null-hypothesis testing:

\(t=\frac{(M_1-M_2)}{s_{(M_1-M_2)}}\)

Still needed: \(df\)

Same as with the error, we add the dfs:

\(df_{total} = df_1 + df_2 = (n_1-1)+(n_2-1) = n_1+n_2-2\)

Here: \(df = 50+50-2=98\)

Part 3: Independent measaures hypothesis testing

What we need

  1. Research question: does espresso intake increase the statistics grade?
  2. Hypotheses:
    • \(H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2\)
    • \(H_1: \mu_1 < \mu_2\)
  3. Data:
    • Group 1: No espresso > \(M_1 = 6.95\), \(SD_1=0.87\), \(n_1=50\)
    • Group 2: 3 espressos > \(M_2 = 7.19\), \(SD_2=1.72\), \(n_2=50\)

Critical t-values region

We know the df: \(df=n_1+n_2-2 = 98\)

Table lookup for \(\alpha=.01\):

df 0.05 0.01 0.005
60 1.671 2.390 2.660
120 1.658 2.358 2.617

Since \(df=98\) is not in the table, we play safe and go for the lower df.

Critical region

Calculating t

Pooled variance via the \(SD\) and \(n\):

\(s_{p}^2=\frac{df_1*s_{1}^2+df_2*s_{2}^2}{df_1 + df_2}\)

\(s_1^2 = 0.87^2 = 0.76\) and \(s_2^2 = 1.72^2 = 2.96\)

So:

\(s_{p}^2=\frac{df_1*0.76+df_2*2.96}{df_1 + df_2}=\frac{49*0.76+49*2.96}{49 + 49}= 1.86\)

Calculating t

Estimated standard error:

\(S_{M_1 - M_2} = \sqrt{{\frac{s^2_p}{n_1}+\frac{s^2_p}{n_2}}}=\sqrt{{\frac{1.86}{50}+\frac{1.86}{50}}} = 0.27\)

To be safe: always pool!

Calculating t

Getting to t:

\(t=\frac{(M_1-M_2)-(\mu_1 - \mu_2)}{s_{(M_1-M_2)}}\)

>

\(t=\frac{(6.95-7.19)-0}{0.27} = \frac{-0.24}{0.27} = -0.89\)

The sample difference is 0.89 times greater than expected if there were no difference.

Note: this is actually not a lot.

Locating t

Interpreting t

The sign of \(t\) depends on the order of \(M_1 - M_2\).

Always use the context here!

Our alternative (one-tailed) hypothesis was \(H_1: \mu_1 < \mu_2\)

Written differently: \(H_1: \mu_1 - \mu_2 < 0\)
